ce:section.ce:para:
The CV responses of bare SPE, PtNi/SPE, N-GQDs/SPE, and PtNi@N-GQDs for the oxidation and reduction of 100 μM DA were investigated through CV in pH 7.0 at 0.05 V/s (Fig. 5
                        a). Bare SPE did not show an obvious peak for DA, demonstrating its poor catalytic activity. The PtNi-modified SPE shows a smaller broad oxidation peak for DA because of the low number of catalytic reactive sites. Alternatively, the SPE with N-GQDs enhanced the redox peak intensities owing to the oxidation of DA to dopamine quinone (DAQ) and DAQ reduced to DA (Scheme 1
                        ). Compared to the other electrodes, PtNi@N-GQDs exhibited a much higher redox current response owing to their excellent conductivity and the synergistic effect of PtNi and N-GQDs. The higher electrocatalytic activity of the PtNi@N-GQDs toward DA due to the presence of O functionality such as hydroxyl (-OH), epoxy (-O-), and carboxyl (-COOH) groups and N functionality such as pyrrolic N, pyridinic N, and graphitic N in the aromatic lattice can provides negative sites to the effective the interaction of PtNi alloy NPs with N-GQDs. PtNi@N-GQDs have introduced some defects and disorders that will enhance catalytic active sites, and the strong adsorption for the DA molecule also offers the high mobility of charge carriers. It is also known that alloy NPs have good catalytic activity toward various electrocatalysis/sensing applications, due to their high stability at neutral pH, synergistic effect of the individual metal atoms, and high chemical resistance. Moreover, our previous work proved that PtNi alloy NPs have good catalytic activity toward hydrogen sulphide sensing, due to their high catalytic activity and stability [29]. Fig. 5b shows the bar diagram for the obtained current responses of 100 μM DA at the different modified electrodes. The sensitivity of the PtNi@N-GQDs/SPE surface was understood by varying the concentrations of DA. Fig. 5c presents the CVs of various [DA] (0–400 μM) on PtNi@N-GQDs/SPE. When the level of DA increased from 0 to 400 μM, the redox current (Ip) increased linearly. The calibration plot of Ipa against the DA concentration is shown in Fig. 5d. The regression and coefficient were as follows: Ipc (μA) = 0.0361 [DA] (μM) + 0.5046 (μA) and R2 = 0.994, respectively.

To investigated the performance of PtNi@N-GQDs in sensing DA at the optimum potential. Fig. 8
                        a shows the i-t response of PtNi@N-GQDs with consecutive injections of DA at 50s intervals under continuous stirring. As shown in Fig. 8a, Ipa increased rapidly with the addition of DA, and a steady-state current was attained within 3s of each addition (Fig. 8c), indicating the rapid adsorption and EC oxidation of DA on the electrode. The obtained current of DA versus concentration was plotted in Fig. 8b. A linear plot was observed for the PtNi@N-GQDs in the range of 0.0125–952 μM with linear regression, and the coefficient was stated as Ipa (μA) = 0.055 [DA] (μM) + 0.783 and R2 = 0.999. The limt of detection (LOD) and limit of quantification (LOQ) were calculated based on the international union of pure and applied chemistry (IUPAC) equation [22]. LOD = 3S/k and LOQ = 10S/k, in this equation, ‘k’ specifies the slope value of the linear plot (0.055 μA/μM), and ‘S’ designates the standard deviation attained from three blank currents (0.0001 μA); the LOD and LOQ were obtained to be 0.0053 μM and 1.79 μM, respectively. The sensitivity of PtNi@N-GQDs was 0.279 μA/μM/cm2. The electroanalytical parameters of the PtNi@N-GQDs were compared with the formerly reported literature (Table 1
                        ). Notably, the sensing parameters of the PtNi@N-GQDs platform were superior to those of DA sensors in the literature.

The practical application of PtNi@N-GQDs was assessed using the amperometric (i-t) detection of DA in human blood serum and urine samples. The real sample was 10 times diluted using PB, and then DA was added. The amperometry current of DA was detected at 0.04 V for the addition of a blood serum sample containing DA (1.25–76.25 μM) in PB (Fig. 10
                        a). Urine was diluted separately with PB and filtered using Whatman filter paper. Afterward, a particular amount of DA was spiked in the urine sample, and the obtained amperometry results are shown in Fig. 10c. The calibration plots of Ipa versus [DA] for the serum and urine are shown in Fig. 10b and d. The recoveries of serum and urine samples were 99.3% and 98.5%, respectively (Table 2
                        ). A real sample study revealed that the PtNi@N-GQDs platform could be exploited as an excellent tool for the detection of DA from substances present in the physical environment.
